<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="31" type="ecology">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="31">Ecology.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="31">
<taxonomicName authority="" authorityName="" class="Coscinodiscophyceae" family="Stephanodiscaceae" genus="Cyclotella" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Cyclotella cryptica" order="Thalassiosirales" pageId="0" pageNumber="31" phylum="Bacillariophyta" rank="species" species="cryptica">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="31">Cyclotella cryptica</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is a planktonic species, known from marine and brackish environments, may be found in high chloride concentrations. It occurs at maximum abundance around 20 °C (
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.1139/b76-097" author="Liu, MS" journalOrPublisher="Canadian Journal of Botany" pageId="0" pageNumber="31" pagination="930 - 937" refId="B83" refString="Liu, MS, Hellebust, JA, 1976. Effects of salinity changes on growth and metabolism of the marine centric diatom Cyclotella cryptica. Canadian Journal of Botany 54 (9): 930 - 937, DOI: https://doi.org/10.1139/b76-097" title="Effects of salinity changes on growth and metabolism of the marine centric diatom Cyclotella cryptica." url="https://doi.org/10.1139/b76-097" volume="54" year="1976">Liu and Hellebust 1976</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.1016/S0380-1330(87)71627-X" author="Makarewicz, JC" journalOrPublisher="Journal of Great Lakes Research" pageId="0" pageNumber="31" pagination="56 - 64" refId="B86" refString="Makarewicz, JC, 1987. Phytoplankton composition, abundance, and distribution: Nearshore Lake Ontario and Oswego River and Harbor. Journal of Great Lakes Research 13 (1): 56 - 64, DOI: https://doi.org/10.1016/S0380-1330(87)71627-X" title="Phytoplankton composition, abundance, and distribution: Nearshore Lake Ontario and Oswego River and Harbor." url="https://doi.org/10.1016/S0380-1330(87)71627-X" volume="13" year="1987">Makarewicz 1987</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.1016/S0380-1330(93)71197-1" author="Mills, EL" journalOrPublisher="Journal of Great Lakes Research" pageId="0" pageNumber="31" pagination="1 - 54" refId="B92" refString="Mills, EL, Leach, JH, Carlton, JT, Secor, CL, 1993. Exotic species in the Great Lakes: A history of biotic crises and anthropogenic introductions. Journal of Great Lakes Research 19 (1): 1 - 54, DOI: https://doi.org/10.1016/S0380-1330(93)71197-1" title="Exotic species in the Great Lakes: A history of biotic crises and anthropogenic introductions." url="https://doi.org/10.1016/S0380-1330(93)71197-1" volume="19" year="1993">Mills et al. 1993</bibRefCitation>
). 
<taxonomicName authority="" authorityName="" class="Coscinodiscophyceae" family="Stephanodiscaceae" genus="Cyclotella" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Cyclotella cryptica" order="Thalassiosirales" pageId="0" pageNumber="31" phylum="Bacillariophyta" rank="species" species="cryptica">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="31">Cyclotella cryptica</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is a saprophilic species (
<bibRefCitation author="Barinova, SS" journalOrPublisher="University of Haifa Publisher, Haifa, Kyiv" pageId="0" pageNumber="31" refId="B6" refString="Barinova, SS, Bilous, OP, Tsarenko, PM, 2019. Algal indication of water bodies in Ukraine: methods and perspectives. University of Haifa Publisher, Haifa, Kyiv" title="Algal indication of water bodies in Ukraine: methods and perspectives." year="2019">Barinova et al. 2019</bibRefCitation>
), requires NO3 as its source of nitrogen and Ni ions in order to grow autotrophically, however is capable of heterotrophic growth in bottom water or mud enriched in glucose and known to grow mesotrophically (
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.1080/00071618400650131" author="Oliveira, L" journalOrPublisher="British Phycological Journal" pageId="0" pageNumber="31" pagination="125 - 134" refId="B99" refString="Oliveira, L, Antia, NJ, 1984. Evidence of nickel ion requirement for autotrophic growth of a marine diatom Cyclotella cryptica with urea serving as nitrogen source. British Phycological Journal 19 (2): 125 - 134, DOI: https://doi.org/10.1080/00071618400650131" title="Evidence of nickel ion requirement for autotrophic growth of a marine diatom Cyclotella cryptica with urea serving as nitrogen source." url="https://doi.org/10.1080/00071618400650131" volume="19" year="1984">Oliveira and Antia 1984</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.1023/A:1008186431492" author="Saros, JE" journalOrPublisher="Journal of Paleolimnology" pageId="0" pageNumber="31" pagination="449 - 453" refId="B109" refString="Saros, JE, Fritz, SC, 2000. Nutrients as a link between ionic concentration/composition and diatom distributions in saline lakes. Journal of Paleolimnology 23 (4): 449 - 453, DOI: https://doi.org/10.1023/A:1008186431492" title="Nutrients as a link between ionic concentration / composition and diatom distributions in saline lakes." url="https://doi.org/10.1023/A:1008186431492" volume="23" year="2000">Saros and Fritz 2000</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="31" type="distribution">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="31">Distribution.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="31">
Valves were identified at the site in the south of Mykolaiv city in the Southern Bug River (Table 
<tableCitation captionStart="Table 1" captionStartId="T1" captionText="Table 1. Species composition of centric diatoms at the investigated sites near Mykolaiv city in the Southern Bug River in the year 2017 (2013 added for station 2)." httpUri="http://table.plazi.org/id/DD3AC92F3D14B9FD95B22148C16CA677" pageId="0" pageNumber="31" tableUuid="DD3AC92F3D14B9FD95B22148C16CA677">1</tableCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="31">
It is a widespread species, recorded for Europe, North America, and Asia (
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.1016/S0380-1330(93)71197-1" author="Mills, EL" journalOrPublisher="Journal of Great Lakes Research" pageId="0" pageNumber="31" pagination="1 - 54" refId="B92" refString="Mills, EL, Leach, JH, Carlton, JT, Secor, CL, 1993. Exotic species in the Great Lakes: A history of biotic crises and anthropogenic introductions. Journal of Great Lakes Research 19 (1): 1 - 54, DOI: https://doi.org/10.1016/S0380-1330(93)71197-1" title="Exotic species in the Great Lakes: A history of biotic crises and anthropogenic introductions." url="https://doi.org/10.1016/S0380-1330(93)71197-1" volume="19" year="1993">Mills et al. 1993</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Guiry, MD" journalOrPublisher="Diatom Research" pageId="0" pageNumber="31" publicationUrl="https://www.algaebase.org" refId="B48" refString="Guiry, MD, Guiry, GM, 2021. AlgaeBase. World-wide electronic publication, National University of Ireland, Galway. https://www.algaebase.org" title="AlgaeBase. World-wide electronic publication, National University of Ireland, Galway." url="https://www.algaebase.org" year="2021">Guiry and Guiry 2021</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
